Yes, I can help you replicate your AppSheet app using Flutter in Visual Studio Code. To get started, we'll take it step by step and recreate your Padel League app, one feature at a time. Here's a basic roadmap:

Step 1: Set Up Flutter Environment in Visual Studio Code

  1. Install Flutter and Dart SDK: If you haven't already, install Flutter SDK and Dart SDK on your machine.
  2. Set Up Visual Studio Code:
    • Install the Flutter and Dart plugins from the VS Code extensions marketplace.
  3. Create a New Flutter Project:
    • Open VS Code and press Ctrl + Shift + P to bring up the command palette.
    • Search for Flutter: New Project and follow the instructions to create a new project.

Step 2: Design the App Layout (Home Page and Navigation)

We'll first focus on creating the home page, navigation bar, and routing between screens like in your AppSheet app.

  1. Create home_page.dart: This will be the main page where the user will land. You can include features like:
    • A navigation bar for accessing the player list, match recording, etc.
    • Buttons for signing up or viewing player stats.
    Example:
    dart
    import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class HomePage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Padel League Home'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: [
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () {
                Navigator.pushNamed(context, '/players');
              },
              child: Text('Player List'),
            ),
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () {
                Navigator.pushNamed(context, '/matches');
              },
              child: Text('Record Match'),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

Step 3: Create Player List Page

Next, you'll want to replicate the player list from AppSheet. In Flutter, you can use ListView to display players, sorted by criteria like rank or name.

  1. Create players_list_page.dart: Example:
    dart
    import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class PlayersListPage extends StatelessWidget {
  final List<String> players = ['Carlos Bogado', 'Miguel Arias', 'Nicolas Valiente']; // Sample player data

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Players List'),
      ),
      body: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: players.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          return ListTile(
            title: Text(players[index]),
            onTap: () {
              // Navigate to player details page
              Navigator.pushNamed(context, '/playerDetails', arguments: players[index]);
            },
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}

Step 4: Add Player Details Page

You’ll create a new page to display individual player details.

  1. Create player_details_page.dart: Example:
    dart
    import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class PlayerDetailsPage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final String player = ModalRoute.of(context)!.settings.arguments as String;

    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text(player),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Text('Details of $player'),
      ),
    );
  }
}

Step 5: Record a Match

You’ll need a page where players can record match results, similar to what you had in AppSheet.

  1. Create match_recording_page.dart: Example:
    dart
    import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class MatchRecordingPage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Record Match'),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Column(
          mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.center,
          children: [
            TextField(
              decoration: InputDecoration(labelText: 'Player A'),
            ),
            TextField(
              decoration: InputDecoration(labelText: 'Player B'),
            ),
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () {
                // Handle match recording logic
              },
              child: Text('Submit Match Result'),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

Step 6: Set Up Routing

Finally, add routes for navigation between the different pages in the main.dart file.

  1. Update main.dart:
    dart
    import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'home_page.dart';
import 'players_list_page.dart';
import 'player_details_page.dart';
import 'match_recording_page.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(MyApp());
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Padel League',
      initialRoute: '/',
      routes: {
        '/': (context) => HomePage(),
        '/players': (context) => PlayersListPage(),
        '/playerDetails': (context) => PlayerDetailsPage(),
        '/matches': (context) => MatchRecordingPage(),
      },
    );
  }
}

To recreate the Form view with rankings, player levels, points, and the result of the last 6 matches in Flutter, we can structure it using a combination of Lists and Tables. The first step is to focus on the player ranking, color levels, and points display.

Let’s start building this step by step.

Step 1: Create the Form View

We will first set up a table-like list that displays:

  • Player rank
  • Player name
  • Points
  • Results of the last 6 matches

Code for the Form View (form_view.dart):

dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class Player {
  final int rank;
  final String name;
  final double points;
  final List<String> lastResults;
  final Color color;

  Player({required this.rank, required this.name, required this.points, required this.lastResults, required this.color});
}

class FormView extends StatelessWidget {
  // Dummy data for now
  final List<Player> players = [
    Player(rank: 1, name: 'Ben Coles', points: 38.9, lastResults: ['W', 'W', 'L', 'W', 'L', 'W'], color: Colors.blue[800]!),
    Player(rank: 2, name: 'Brett Holman', points: 37.9, lastResults: ['L', 'W', 'W', 'L', 'W', 'W'], color: Colors.blue[800]!),
    Player(rank: 3, name: 'Liam Serneholt', points: 37.65, lastResults: ['W', 'W', 'W', 'L', 'W', 'L'], color: Colors.blue[800]!),
    // Add more players here as needed...
  ];

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Form'),
        backgroundColor: Colors.blue,
      ),
      body: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: players.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          final player = players[index];
          return Card(
            margin: EdgeInsets.all(8.0),
            child: ListTile(
              leading: CircleAvatar(
                backgroundColor: player.color,  // Color based on ranking
                child: Text(player.rank.toString(), style: TextStyle(color: Colors.white)),
              ),
              title: Text(player.name),
              subtitle: Text('Points: ${player.points}'),
              trailing: Row(
                mainAxisSize: MainAxisSize.min,
                children: player.lastResults.map((result) {
                  return Padding(
                    padding: const EdgeInsets.symmetric(horizontal: 2.0),
                    child: _buildResultIcon(result),
                  );
                }).toList(),
              ),
            ),
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }

  Widget _buildResultIcon(String result) {
    Color color;
    switch (result) {
      case 'W':
        color = Colors.green;
        break;
      case 'L':
        color = Colors.red;
        break;
      case 'D':
        color = Colors.yellow;
        break;
      default:
        color = Colors.grey;
    }
    return CircleAvatar(
      backgroundColor: color,
      radius: 10,
      child: Text(result, style: TextStyle(color: Colors.white, fontSize: 12)),
    );
  }
}

Explanation:

  1. Player Data: We created a Player class that holds rank, name, points, last match results, and the associated color.
  2. Rank Color: We are using a CircleAvatar widget to show the rank with different colors depending on the player's position.
  3. Results: The lastResults are shown as small colored circles: Green for wins (W), Red for losses (L), and Yellow for draws (D).

dart

import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class FormView extends StatelessWidget {

  Widget build(BuildContext context) {

      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Form View'),

      ),

          children: [

                  return ListTile(
                    leading: CircleAvatar(
                      backgroundColor: Colors.blue,
                      child: Text('${index + 1}'),  // Player ranking position
                    ),
                    title: Text('Player ${index + 1}'),
                    subtitle: Text('Points: ${(index + 1) * 10}.0'),
                    trailing: Wrap(
                      spacing: 6,
                      children: List.generate(
                        6,  // Last 6 matches results
                        (matchIndex) => Icon(
                          Icons.circle,  // Icon to represent win/loss
                          color: (matchIndex % 2 == 0) ? Colors.green : Colors.red,
                          size: 10,
                        ),
                      ),
                    ),
                  );
                },
              ),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

  • The green/red circles represent the last 6 matches (green for wins and red for losses). You can modify the logic here to suit your specific use case.

If you're working in Visual Studio Code but still want to visualize your app using an emulator, you can use Android Emulators or iOS Simulators by following the steps below.

1. Setting Up an Android Emulator in Visual Studio Code

Prerequisites:

  • Android Studio must be installed because the emulator is part of the Android SDK tools.

Steps to Set Up the Android Emulator:

  1. Install Android Studio:

    • Download and install Android Studio if you haven't already.

  2. Set Up the Emulator in Android Studio:

    • Open Android Studio.
    • Go to Tools > AVD Manager (Android Virtual Device Manager).
    • Click Create Virtual Device.
    • Select a hardware profile (like Pixel 3 or any device you prefer).
    • Choose a system image (API level) and download it if necessary.
    • Click Finish to create the virtual device.

  3. Start the Emulator:

    • Open AVD Manager in Android Studio and click the Play button next to the emulator you created.

  4. Configure the Emulator in Visual Studio Code:

    • Once the emulator is running, open Visual Studio Code.
    • Press Ctrl + Shift + P (or Cmd + Shift + P on Mac) to open the Command Palette.
    • Type Flutter: Select Device and select your emulator from the list (you should see your running emulator).

  5. Run the App:

    • Run your Flutter app by typing flutter run in the terminal, or by pressing F5 in Visual Studio Code.

2. Setting Up an iOS Simulator in Visual Studio Code (macOS only)

Prerequisites:

Steps to Set Up the iOS Simulator:

  1. Install Xcode:

    • Open Xcode and agree to the terms and conditions.
    • Go to Xcode > Preferences > Components, and install the desired simulator.

  1. Enable Developer Mode on the Phone:

    • Go to Settings > About phone > Tap Build number 7 times.
    • Enable USB Debugging in the Developer options menu.

  2. Connect your Device to Your Computer:

    • Plug your Android phone into your computer using a USB cable.
    • In Visual Studio Code, press Ctrl + Shift + P (or Cmd + Shift + P on Mac), type Flutter: Select Device, and choose your connected device.
    • Run your app with flutter run or F5.

For iOS Devices (macOS only):

  1. Connect your iPhone to Your Mac.
  2. Trust Your Computer:
    • When you connect the device, your iPhone will ask you to trust this computer. Tap "Trust" and enter your passcode.

    • You’ll see the app running on your physical iPhone.

match_results_view.dart

dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class MatchResultsView extends StatelessWidget {
  final List<PlayerResult> players = [
    PlayerResult(rank: 1, name: 'Ben Coles', played: 20, won: 12, drawn: 1, lost: 7, winPercentage: 60, setsWon: 28, setsLost: 18),
    PlayerResult(rank: 2, name: 'Brett Holman', played: 10, won: 7, drawn: 2, lost: 1, winPercentage: 70, setsWon: 16, setsLost: 6),
    PlayerResult(rank: 3, name: 'Liam Serneholt', played: 17, won: 11, drawn: 0, lost: 6, winPercentage: 64, setsWon: 23, setsLost: 13),
    // Add more players as needed
  ];

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Match Results'),
        backgroundColor: Colors.blue,
      ),
      body: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: players.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          final player = players[index];
          return ListTile(
            leading: CircleAvatar(
              backgroundColor: _getColorForRank(player.rank),
              child: Text('${player.rank}'),
            ),
            title: Text(player.name),
            subtitle: Row(
              children: [
                Expanded(child: Text('P: ${player.played}')),
                Expanded(child: Text('W: ${player.won}')),
                Expanded(child: Text('D: ${player.drawn}')),
                Expanded(child: Text('L: ${player.lost}')),
                Expanded(child: Text('${player.winPercentage}%')),
                Expanded(child: Text('Sets: ${player.setsWon}-${player.setsLost}')),
              ],
            ),
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }

  // Color based on rank
  Color _getColorForRank(int rank) {
    if (rank <= 15) {
      return Colors.blue[900]!;
    } else if (rank <= 30) {
      return Colors.blue[300]!;
    } else if (rank <= 50) {
      return Colors.yellow[700]!;
    } else if (rank <= 70) {
      return Colors.green[600]!;
    } else if (rank <= 90) {
      return Colors.orange[600]!;
    } else {
      return Colors.red[600]!;
    }
  }
}

// PlayerResult class
class PlayerResult {
  final int rank;
  final String name;
  final int played;
  final int won;
  final int drawn;
  final int lost;
  final int winPercentage;
  final int setsWon;
  final int setsLost;

  PlayerResult({
    required this.rank,
    required this.name,
    required this.played,
    required this.won,
    required this.drawn,
    required this.lost,
    required this.winPercentage,
    required this.setsWon,
    required this.setsLost,
  });
}

dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'form_view.dart';  // Form view (Player Rankings)
import 'match_results_view.dart';  // Match Results view

class MainDashboard extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _MainDashboardState createState() => _MainDashboardState();
}

class _MainDashboardState extends State<MainDashboard> {
  int _selectedIndex = 0;

  static const List<Widget> widgetOptions = <Widget>[
    BookingsPage(), // First tab: Bookings page
    TableTabs(),    // Second tab: Table (which holds Form and Match Results)
  ];

  void _onItemTapped(int index) {
    setState(() {
      _selectedIndex = index;
    });
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Padeltrax Dashboard'),
        backgroundColor: Colors.blue,
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: widgetOptions.elementAt(_selectedIndex),
      ),
      bottomNavigationBar: BottomNavigationBar(
        items: const <BottomNavigationBarItem>[
          BottomNavigationBarItem(
            icon: Icon(Icons.calendar_today),
            label: 'Bookings',
          ),
          BottomNavigationBarItem(
            icon: Icon(Icons.table_chart),
            label: 'Table',
          ),
        ],
        currentIndex: _selectedIndex,
        selectedItemColor: Colors.blue,
        onTap: _onItemTapped,
      ),
    );
  }
}

// TableTabs widget for TabBar containing Form and Match Results
class TableTabs extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return DefaultTabController(
      length: 2,
      child: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(
          title: Text('Table'),
          backgroundColor: Colors.blue,
          bottom: TabBar(
            tabs: [
              Tab(text: 'Form'),
              Tab(text: 'Match Results'),
            ],
          ),
        ),
        body: TabBarView(
          children: [
            FormView(), // First tab: Form (Player rankings and results)
            MatchResultsView(), // Second tab: Match Results
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

Step 1: Create the Schedule Page Layout

The first step is to create a new schedule_page.dart file that will contain the layout for the schedule. This layout will include tabs for each day and a section for each timeslot.

Here’s how the structure will look:

  3. A list of players under each timeslot

1.1 schedule_page.dart

dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

class SchedulePage extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _SchedulePageState createState() => _SchedulePageState();
}

class _SchedulePageState extends State<SchedulePage> with SingleTickerProviderStateMixin {
  TabController? _tabController;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _tabController = TabController(length: 5, vsync: this); // 5 tabs for Monday to Friday
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    _tabController?.dispose();
    super.dispose();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Schedule'),
        backgroundColor: Colors.blue,
        bottom: TabBar(
          controller: _tabController,
          tabs: [
            Tab(text: 'Monday'),
            Tab(text: 'Tuesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Wednesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Thursday'),
            Tab(text: 'Friday'),
          ],
        ),
      ),
      body: TabBarView(
        controller: _tabController,
        children: [
          _buildDaySchedule('Monday'),
          _buildDaySchedule('Tuesday'),
          _buildDaySchedule('Wednesday'),
          _buildDaySchedule('Thursday'),
          _buildDaySchedule('Friday'),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }

  // Method to build the schedule for each day
  Widget _buildDaySchedule(String day) {
    return Column(
      crossAxisAlignment: CrossAxisAlignment.start,
      children: [
        Padding(
          padding: const EdgeInsets.all(8.0),
          child: Text(
            '$day - Early Padel Session',
            style: TextStyle(fontSize: 18, fontWeight: FontWeight.bold),
          ),
        ),
        _buildPlayerList(day, 'Early'),
        Padding(
          padding: const EdgeInsets.all(8.0),
          child: Text(
            '$day - Later Padel Session',
            style: TextStyle(fontSize: 18, fontWeight: FontWeight.bold),
          ),
        ),
        _buildPlayerList(day, 'Later'),
      ],
    );
  }

  // Method to build the player list for each timeslot
  Widget _buildPlayerList(String day, String timeslot) {
    // This will be dynamically filled with player data from sign-ups
    List<String> players = _getPlayersForTimeslot(day, timeslot);

    return Expanded(
      child: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: players.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          return ListTile(
            title: Text(players[index]),
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }

  // Temporary mock function to get players based on day and timeslot
  List<String> _getPlayersForTimeslot(String day, String timeslot) {
    // Mock player data, replace with actual sign-up data
    if (day == 'Monday' && timeslot == 'Early') {
      return ['Player 1', 'Player 2', 'Player 3'];
    } else if (day == 'Monday' && timeslot == 'Later') {
      return ['Player 4', 'Player 5', 'Player 6'];
    }
    return [];
  }
}

              child: Text('Early Timeslot'),
            ),
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: () {
                _bookTimeslot(context, day, 'Later');
              },
              child: Text('Later Timeslot'),
            ),
          ],
        ),
        SizedBox(height: 20),
      ],
    );
  }

  // Method to book the timeslot and store the sign-up data
  void _bookTimeslot(BuildContext context, String day, String timeslot) {
    playerSignUps.add({
      'playerName': player.name,
      'day': day,
      'timeslot': timeslot,
    });

    ScaffoldMessenger.of(context).showSnackBar(SnackBar(
      content: Text('${player.name} signed up for $timeslot session on $day'),
    ));
  }

Step 3: Update the Schedule Page to Display Real Data

In the SchedulePage, we need to update _getPlayersForTimeslot to return real sign-up data from playerSignUps.

Here’s the updated function in schedule_page.dart:

dart
List<String> _getPlayersForTimeslot(String day, String timeslot) {
  List<String> players = [];
  
  for (var signUp in playerSignUps) {
    if (signUp['day'] == day && signUp['timeslot'] == timeslot) {
      players.add(signUp['playerName']);
    }
  }

  return players;
}

dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'bookings_page.dart'; // Import the Player class

class SchedulePage extends StatefulWidget {

  SchedulePage({required this.players});

  @override
  _SchedulePageState createState() => _SchedulePageState();
}

class _SchedulePageState extends State<SchedulePage> with SingleTickerProviderStateMixin {
  late TabController _tabController;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _tabController = TabController(length: 5, vsync: this); // 5 tabs for Monday to Friday
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    _tabController.dispose();
    super.dispose();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Schedule'),
        bottom: TabBar(
          controller: _tabController,
          tabs: [
            Tab(text: 'Monday'),
            Tab(text: 'Tuesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Wednesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Thursday'),
            Tab(text: 'Friday'),
          ],
        ),

      body: TabBarView(

          buildDaySchedule('Tuesday'),
          buildDaySchedule('Wednesday'),
          buildDaySchedule('Thursday'),
          buildDaySchedule('Friday'),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }

  // Build schedule for each day
  Widget buildDaySchedule(String day) {

        Expanded(child: buildPlayerList(earlyPlayers)),
        SizedBox(height: 10),
        Text('Later Padel Session', style: TextStyle(fontWeight: FontWeight.bold, fontSize: 16)),
        Expanded(child: buildPlayerList(laterPlayers)),
      ],
    );

  // Build player list for the session

2. Schedule Page (schedule_page.dart)

dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'bookings_page.dart'; // Import Player class

class SchedulePage extends StatefulWidget {
  final List<Player> players;

  SchedulePage({required this.players}); // Accept players list

  @override
  _SchedulePageState createState() => _SchedulePageState();
}

class _SchedulePageState extends State<SchedulePage> with SingleTickerProviderStateMixin {
  late TabController _tabController;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _tabController = TabController(length: 5, vsync: this); // 5 tabs for Monday to Friday
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    _tabController.dispose();
    super.dispose();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Schedule'),
        bottom: TabBar(
          controller: _tabController,
          tabs: [
            Tab(text: 'Monday'),
            Tab(text: 'Tuesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Wednesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Thursday'),
            Tab(text: 'Friday'),
          ],
        ),
      ),
      body: TabBarView(
        controller: _tabController,
        children: [
          buildDaySchedule('Monday'),
          buildDaySchedule('Tuesday'),
          buildDaySchedule('Wednesday'),
          buildDaySchedule('Thursday'),
          buildDaySchedule('Friday'),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }

  // Widget for each day
  Widget buildDaySchedule(String day) {
    List<Player> playersForDay = widget.players.where((player) => player.signedDay == day).toList();

    return Column(
      children: [
        SizedBox(height: 10),
        Text('Early Padel Session', style: TextStyle(fontWeight: FontWeight.bold, fontSize: 16)),
        Expanded(child: buildPlayerList(playersForDay, 'early')),
        SizedBox(height: 10),
        Text('Later Padel Session', style: TextStyle(fontWeight: FontWeight.bold, fontSize: 16)),
        Expanded(child: buildPlayerList(playersForDay, 'later')),
      ],
    );
  }

  // Widget to display the player list based on session type and day
  Widget buildPlayerList(List<Player> players, String sessionType) {
    List<Player> playersForSession = players.where((player) => player.signedTimeslot == sessionType).toList();

    return ListView.builder(
      itemCount: playersForSession.length,
      itemBuilder: (context, index) {
        final player = playersForSession[index];
        return ListTile(
          leading: CircleAvatar(child: Text('${index + 1}')),
          title: Text(player.name),
          subtitle: Text('Rank: ${index + 10}'), // Replace with actual player rank
        );
      },
    );
  }
}

class _SchedulePageState extends State<SchedulePage>
    with SingleTickerProviderStateMixin {
  late TabController _tabController;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _tabController = TabController(length: 5, vsync: this); // 5 tabs for Monday to Friday

class _SchedulePageState extends State<SchedulePage> with SingleTickerProviderStateMixin {
  late TabController _tabController;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _tabController = TabController(length: 5, vsync: this);
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    _tabController.dispose();
    super.dispose();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text('Schedule'),
        bottom: TabBar(
          controller: _tabController,
          tabs: [
            Tab(text: 'Monday'),
            Tab(text: 'Tuesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Wednesday'),
            Tab(text: 'Thursday'),
            Tab(text: 'Friday'),
          ],
        ),
      ),
      body: TabBarView(
        controller: _tabController,
        children: [
          buildDaySchedule('Monday', widget.players),
          buildDaySchedule('Tuesday', widget.players),
          buildDaySchedule('Wednesday', widget.players),
          buildDaySchedule('Thursday', widget.players),
          buildDaySchedule('Friday', widget.players),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }

      ],
    );

    return ListView.builder(

          subtitle: Text('Rank: ${players[index].rating}'), 
        );
      },
    );
  }
}

Add the Save Button to bookings_page.dart

  1. Add a Save button to the bottom of the player's booking page.
  2. Store the player's selection (day and time slot) in a list or map when the button is clicked.

Here's how we can modify the bookings_page.dart file:

dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'player.dart'; // Import player model

class BookingsPage extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _BookingsPageState createState() => _BookingsPageState();
}

class _BookingsPageState extends State<BookingsPage> {
  // Example: Map to store each player's bookings
  Map<String, Map<String, String>> playerBookings = {};

  // List of players (for demonstration)
  List<Player> players = [
    Player(name: 'Player 1', rating: 5.0, profileImage: 'assets/profile1.png'),
    Player(name: 'Player 2', rating: 5.0, profileImage: 'assets/profile2.png'),
  ];

  // Example of player time slot selection for the week
  Map<String, String> selectedSlots = {
    'Monday': 'Early',
    'Wednesday': 'Later',
  };

  // Method to save the player's booking
  void saveBooking(Player player, Map<String, String> selectedSlots) {
    setState(() {
      playerBookings[player.name] = selectedSlots;
      print("${player.name} saved bookings: $selectedSlots");
    });
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text('Bookings for Player')),
      body: ListView.builder(
        itemCount: players.length,
        itemBuilder: (context, index) {
          Player player = players[index];

          return Column(
            crossAxisAlignment: CrossAxisAlignment.start,
            children: [
              ListTile(
                leading: CircleAvatar(
                  backgroundImage: AssetImage(player.profileImage),
                ),
                title: Text('Player: ${player.name}'),
                subtitle: Text('Rating: ${player.rating}'),
              ),
              // Time slot buttons for each day (simplified for demonstration)
              Row(
                mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.spaceEvenly,
                children: [
                  TextButton(onPressed: () {}, child: Text('Early Timeslot')),
                  TextButton(onPressed: () {}, child: Text('Later Timeslot')),
                  TextButton(onPressed: () {}, child: Text('Play Either')),
                ],
              ),
              SizedBox(height: 20),
              // Save Button
              Center(
                child: ElevatedButton(
                  onPressed: () {
                    // Call the saveBooking method when clicked
                    saveBooking(player, selectedSlots);
                  },
                  child: Text('Save Booking'),
                ),
              ),
              Divider(),
            ],
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}

Step 2: Modify schedule_page.dart to Show Player Bookings

Next, we'll modify the schedule_page.dart to display the players in two columns based on their saved time slot for each day.

We'll organize the players into "Early" and "Later" time slots for each day. Here's an outline of how the schedule page can be modified:

Modify the Schedule Page

  1. Check the stored bookings for each player.
  2. Display them in the appropriate columns based on their selections.
dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'player.dart'; // Import the player model

class SchedulePage extends StatelessWidget {
  // List of players (to be updated based on actual bookings)
  final List<Player> players = [
    Player(name: 'Player 1', rating: 5.0, profileImage: 'assets/profile1.png', signedDay: 'Monday', signedTimeslot: 'Early'),
    Player(name: 'Player 2', rating: 5.0, profileImage: 'assets/profile2.png', signedDay: 'Wednesday', signedTimeslot: 'Later'),
  ];

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return DefaultTabController(
      length: 5, // Monday to Friday
      child: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(
          title: Text('Schedule'),
          bottom: TabBar(
            tabs: [
              Tab(text: 'Monday'),
              Tab(text: 'Tuesday'),
              Tab(text: 'Wednesday'),
              Tab(text: 'Thursday'),
              Tab(text: 'Friday'),
            ],
          ),
        ),
        body: TabBarView(
          children: [
            buildDaySchedule('Monday'),
            buildDaySchedule('Tuesday'),
            buildDaySchedule('Wednesday'),
            buildDaySchedule('Thursday'),
            buildDaySchedule('Friday'),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }

  Widget buildDaySchedule(String day) {
    // Filter players based on day and timeslot
    List<Player> earlyPlayers = players.where((p) => p.signedDay == day && p.signedTimeslot == 'Early').toList();
    List<Player> laterPlayers = players.where((p) => p.signedDay == day && p.signedTimeslot == 'Later').toList();

    return Row(
      children: [
        // Column for Early Timeslot
        Expanded(
          child: Column(
            children: [
              Text('Early Padel Session', style: TextStyle(fontWeight: FontWeight.bold)),
              ...earlyPlayers.map((player) => ListTile(
                    leading: CircleAvatar(backgroundImage: AssetImage(player.profileImage)),
                    title: Text(player.name),
                    subtitle: Text('Rating: ${player.rating}'),
                  )),
            ],
          ),
        ),
        // Column for Later Timeslot
        Expanded(
          child: Column(
            children: [
              Text('Later Padel Session', style: TextStyle(fontWeight: FontWeight.bold)),
              ...laterPlayers.map((player) => ListTile(
                    leading: CircleAvatar(backgroundImage: AssetImage(player.profileImage)),
                    title: Text(player.name),
                    subtitle: Text('Rating: ${player.rating}'),
                  )),
            ],
          ),
        ),
      ],
    );
  }
}

  2. Schedule Display in schedule_page.dart: Displays players based on their saved day and time slot in two columns (Early and Later).
